speleothems are both the most common and also the
most useful as climatic records. Techniques for
dating cave sediments include radiocarbon and U/Th
dating of speleothems and paleomagnetic reversals
and cosmogenic isotope dating of clastic
sediments. Cosmogenic isotope dating of elastic
sediments in caves with multiple levels or which
occur at different elevations provide a geomorphic
record of cave ages and river system evolution over
the past 5 Ma. Isotope profiles, trace element
profiles, color banding and luminescence profiles of
speleothems, mainly stalagmites, produce a detailed
paleoclimate record with very high time resolution
over the past several hundred thousand years. There
is potential application of these methods to late
Holocene climates with implications for evaluation
of current concern over global warming.},
