outer ring in the sea-level pressure field is much
broader, encompassing the entire tropics. During
cold winters the NAM signature is much more
pronounced over the Pacific sector: the sea-level
pressure pattern exhibits a North Pacific center of
action, positively correlated with the Atlantic
center, and pronounced deflections of the storm
track are also evident. It is suggested that the
former features are associated with the equatorward
displacement of the jet stream and the storm tracks
during warm winters of the ENSO cycle and the latter
is related to the the more pronounced break in the
subtropical jet stream over the Pacific sector
