events independently of satellite data. Mean
absolute errors between the model-predicted and
AVHRR-observed SOS/EOS ranged from 5.1 to 20.3
days. SOS errors were uniformly lower than EOS
errors. SOS models for the deciduous broadleaf
forest and grassland plant functional types produced
lower errors than use of the climatological SOS
values while all other models produced errors higher
than those obtained from the climatological
dates. Based on this criterion for success, we
suggest that the AVHRR may not be appropriate for
further development of prognostic land surface
phenology models. However, an intercomparison of
phenological dates from an independent spring index
model, our model predictions, and the AVHRR
observations indicated that interannual predictions
from our models may be superior to the satellite
data upon which they are based, implying that a
further comparison between models based on the AVHRR
and newer, superior sensors, should be
conducted. (c) 2006 Elsevier B.V All rights
reserved.},
author = {Kathuroju, N and White, M A and Symanzik, J and Schwartz, M D and Powell, J A and Nemani, R R},
journal = {Ecological Modelling},
keywords = {budburst climate change senescence leaf out growin},
