yr. The spread of Austrocedrus is explained by a
shift towards a cooler and wetter climate in the
middle and late Holocene. The change to a
surface-fire regime is consistent with increased
interannual climate variability and the onset or
strengthening of ENSO. The present-day mixed forest
dominated by Nothofagus and Austrocedrus was
established in the last few millennia. (c) 2006
