records. Tree-ring data, which provide annual
resolution, range throughout the Southwest, extend
back in time for up to 1000 yr or more in various
forests of the Southwest, and integrate well the
influences of both temperature and precipitation,
are useful for this assessment of climate of the
Southwest. Tree growth of mid-elevation forests
typically responds to moisture availability during
the growing season, and a commonly used climate
variable in paleo-precipitation studies is the
Palmer Drought Severity Index (PDSI), which is a
